Bring a #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp}.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nests{2} and bring back to the boil. Cook until
tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{}. 
> TIP: Run the noodles under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} or #wok{} on
medium-high heat.

Once the oil is hot, add the @diced chicken breast{260%g} and season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Fry, stirring occasionally, until browned,
~{5-6%minutes}.
> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Meanwhile, halve the @plums{2}, remove the stones and chop each half into three
wedges.

Trim the @pak choi{1}, then thinly slice widthways.

Trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{1}.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Lower the heat to medium and add the plums and @sugar{1} to the chicken.

Stir-fry until the plums start to colour, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and @ginger puree{1/2%tsp} along with half the spring onion
and as many @chilli flakes{1} as you'd like (careful - they're hot).

Stir-fry for ~{1%minute} more.

Add the pak choi and stir-fry until just soft, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the @hoisin sauce{32%g}, @ketjap manis{25%ml} and @water{2%tbsp}, ensuring
everything is well coated.

Add the cooked noodles to the pan. Stir together and cook until everything is
piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.
> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Share the chicken and plum stir-fry between your #bowls{}.

Scatter over the @salted peanuts{25%g} and remaining spring onion to serve. Enjoy!